Previously, I calculated the most likely probabilities of P(Yoon) and P(Lee) that could have generated results of the poll. These probabilities can be described as "what is the probability that a pollster will vote for Yoon/Lee" that could have most likely generated results of that poll.
havent been following well enough, going to consensus in the close here

I'm just going to raise my bet since very few incumbent parties, if any, have survived the COVID-19 pandemic. I understand the Democratic Party of Korea won the 2020 legislative election (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_South_Korean_legislative_election) but apparently there is growing discontent among Koreans about restriction measures and higher cases (https://www.dw.com/en/south-korea-business-owners-shave-heads-in-covid-19-curb-protest/av-60578011).
Thanks @alter_hugo for your comments! I really appreciate them!
According to 3 Mar opinion polls of the Wikipedia site as of 7 Mar 2022, https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2022_South_Korean_presidential_election#Opinion_polling

According to three out four polls published between Sunday 27 and Monday 28, compiled by Statista (https://www.statista.com/statistics/1286668/south-korea-voting-intention-for-presidential-election-by-polling-institute/) People Power Party would beat the Democratic Party of Korea by a 2.2% to a 5.1% margin (the fourth poll predicts a tie). As @monicaflorio and @DomHajduk pointed out, People Party's candidate dropping out and endorsing People Power Party would likely tip the balance even more - even if only half the votes of their former 10% is transferred to People Power Party. Undecided poll respondents do not reach 8% in most cases, so their contribution in the election might not be crucial. Though it is important to monitor any events unfolding during the following days.
According to Gallup polling two weeks ago, the election was too close to call.
Welp, overnight the Yun - Ahn unity ticket was announced (https://www.reuters.com/world/asia-pacific/skorea-presidential-candidate-backs-conservative-may-tip-tight-race-2022-03-03/).

from some current news coverage - seems like how the prospective candidates react to ongoing ukrainian events may influence - but reporting seems to be pretty even split on who may win

While I do think Yoon has a slight edge, I think the current forecast is overly confident in Yoon's favour. While Yoon does appear to have a slight edge in the polling, they have shown a tightening of the race in recent weeks.

Dem approval rating sharply up week on week, Lee courting third party voters, and a return to "form" - gaffes and bumbling - by Yun gets this back to a toss-up. Yun still somewhat ahead, but we have one more debate to go and just over a week, and the trend has swung back to where it was at the start of the year. If Lee ends up winning, he can thank Ahn Cheol-su, as he will need to redirect his supporters to himself, or at least keep them from going (returning?) to Yun.

PP has withdrawn offer to merge campaigns with PPP. Presumably PPP is confident the polls are going its way. Slightly adjusting my odds in favour of the PPP therefore.

New polling indicates crystallization of trends that have emerged in the last month - despite being widely seen as more capable, the county just is not feeling Lee, who is now 7 points behind. Broader dynamics and party ID ultimately more impactful than candidate characteristics - unless Mr gaffe per day missteps significantly in the final stretch.

Improving likelihood of PPP winning according to opinion polls. PPP appears to be in talks with PP to merge campaigns, which would significantly boost its chances. However negative campaigning makes the race highly volatile.
Go with the flow.

It still looks like anything could happen. Games are being played with Ann as the 3rd candidate. Are the PPP trying to force him out or are they serious about merging? 14 Feb is the deadline for that.

"A Realmeter poll of 3,031 voters commissioned by OhmyNews that ran from Jan. 9 to Friday showed Yoon leading with 40.6 percent support, up 6.5 percentage points from a week earlier. He is followed by Lee Jae-myung of the ruling Democratic Party at 36.7 percent, down 3.4 percent points on-week. Yoon was leading the race with 3.9 percentage points distance from Lee, which is outside the margin of error at plus or minus 1.8 percentage points with a 95 percent confidence level for the latest survey." http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20220117000692

Pretty consistent polling of roughly 35-40% vs 30%, with not one recent poll in favor of PPP candidate. So if election were today I think the odds are something like 90-95%. However the election is, critically, NOT today and there is lots of time for news to trickle in.

https://asia.nikkei.com/Spotlight/South-Korea-election/With-candidate-battered-South-Korea-conservatives-size-up-Ahn Ahn Cheol-soo of the PP looks to be doing well in polls, hope has risen from only a few pc to 17pc and has a nice upward trajectory. If this keeps going it could split votes 30/30/30 and then anything could happen.

Opinion polls are still close and reading the articles below, anything could happen to make the result swing either way as both candidates are new to the National Assembly and are handling the change in what seems a not overly competent way and both have corruption allegations https://foreignpolicy.com/2022/01/06/conservatives-south-korea-presidential-election/ https://www.aljazeera.com/opinions/2021/12/22/sk-presidential-election-choosing-the-lesser-of-the-two-evils

https://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/2022/01/02/national/2022presidential/Ahn-Cheolsoo-presidential-election-campaign/20220102170746808.html PPP hasn't been polling as well in the past month or so. "Yoon's ratings suffered in the most recent polls after allegations of his wife using false credentials and disunity within his election campaign". Not sure if there is more to it than that as news is sparse, but as it stands, recovery seems possible.
In the 6th Republic of South Korea, the Presidency has been dominated by either a Conservative (C) or Liberal (L) - https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Presidential_elections_in_South_Korea

Very various opinions in our working group, and here is the result of the compromise. DPK comes with legacy, PPP fresher gives tangible chances to PPP. Statistically, DPK should take it, and the dynamic of the last days, in particular around young voters will be decisive.
Opinion polls look thin on the ground so far, but looks fairly level pegging at the moment. More research to be done https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2022_South_Korean_presidential_election

In Korea, the president is restricted to a single five-year term in office, so there is no incumbent. The Democratic Party currently has 180 of 300 seats in the National Assembly "However, by April 2021, President Moon's approval rating fell into the low 30s, the lowest of his term"
Sheeple are everywhere.
The battle of the crooks vs the crookest, in the spirited way that Koreans fight, the crookest will win.
